<h1 class="hero-h">The gym <em style="font-family:'Instrument Serif',serif;font-style:italic;color:#00C853;">pre-sale playbook.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">Presale is the single highest-leverage activity in opening a new gym. Done well, it pays for the cash-valley months that kill most new gyms. Done badly — or skipped — and you'll spend the next 12 months trying to catch up to a ramp that's already behind. This is the 90-day playbook, with the offer design, channel mix, AI agent nurture sequences, and conversion benchmarks operators actually hit.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The honest framing</span>
<h2 class="h2">Why presale matters more than anything else in opening</h2>
<p class="body">The math: a small boutique opening with 30 members on day one will burn through reserves in months 4-6. The same boutique opening with 150 founding members at $79/month (~$12K MRR baseline) has a 6-9 month runway built in — enough cushion to absorb the inevitable ramp slowness.</p>
<p class="body">That cushion isn't a nice-to-have. It's the difference between surviving month 9 with a viable gym and shutting down because rent + payroll + debt service ate the reserves before membership ramped.</p>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> Every founding member sold in presale is worth roughly 1.5x a post-launch member sold at full price — because they show up earlier in the cash-flow cycle, when each dollar of revenue prevents a dollar of reserve burn.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The offer</span>
<h2 class="h2">Founding-member offer design</h2>
<p class="body">The offer has four components. Get any one wrong and conversion collapses.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>1. Locked-in lifetime rate.</strong> 60-70% of grand-open price. Locked for as long as they remain a member, not just year one. Example: grand-open price $129/mo → founding rate $89/mo for life.</li>
<li><strong>2. Cap the cohort.</strong> "First 100 founding members" or "first 200." Creates real urgency. Don't lie about the cap — operators who fake scarcity get caught and the brand never recovers.</li>
<li><strong>3. Exclusive perks the post-launch members won't get.</strong> Priority class booking, free initial assessment with a coach, branded swag, founder dinner with the owner, founding-member wall plaque, first dibs on personal training slots.</li>
<li><strong>4. Easy commitment terms.</strong> No long contract for the founding tier (or month-to-month after a 3-6 month minimum). Founders are taking a risk on you — reduce friction.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">A real example</h3>
<div class="callout"><p>"Founding 150: $89/month locked for life · No long-term contract · Priority booking on all classes · Complimentary initial assessment + body comp · Limited to the first 150 members through the door. Membership opens to general public at $129/month on grand open."</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">The 90-day timeline</span>
<h2 class="h2">When to do what</h2>
<h3 class="h3">Days 1-15: Foundation</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Landing page live with founding-member offer, lead capture form, founder photo + story, construction-progress photos.</li>
<li>Meta Pixel + Google Tag installed. UTMs structured for each channel.</li>
<li>Signage on the construction barriers — biggest hyperlocal exposure you'll ever have. Spend on this.</li>
<li>AI agent platform configured: lead nurture sequences, tour-booking flow, no-show recovery, payment processing.</li>
<li>Founding-member CRM list set up with stage-based tags.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Days 15-45: Active acquisition</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Meta ads (lead-gen objective): $40-$80/day budget targeting 5-12 minute drive-time radius. Creative: founder talking-to-camera + construction-progress reel.</li>
<li>Google Local Service Ads + Search: defensive coverage on "[city] gym," "[neighborhood] boutique fitness," "personal trainer near me."</li>
<li>Partnerships: 3-5 adjacent businesses (coffee, juice, athleisure, daycare, physical therapy) running cross-promotion in exchange for partner-discount access.</li>
<li>Email nurture sequence: 7 emails over 14 days, blending construction progress + founder story + social proof + offer reminder.</li>
<li>Weekly "tour weekends" at the construction site: hard hats, real walkthrough, sign-up-in-person.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Days 45-75: Conversion sprint</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li>Re-target everyone who visited the landing page but didn't book a tour with a "X spots left" creative.</li>
<li>Founder hosts 2-3 founding-member info sessions at the construction site or nearby cafe.</li>
<li>Referral program activated: every founding member gets the next month free if they refer one new founding member.</li>
<li>AI agent handles no-show recovery for tour bookings (typically recovers 25-40% of no-shows for a tour reschedule).</li>
<li>Press: pitch local lifestyle/business outlets on the gym opening. One write-up in a local outlet generates 30-80 inbound leads in most markets.</li>
</ul>
<h3 class="h3">Days 75-90: Close</h3>
<ul class="ul">
<li>"Last 30 spots" announcement (only if real). Drives the procrastinators.</li>
<li>Founder personal outreach (text + call) to every lead that toured but didn't convert.</li>
<li>Founding-member onboarding sequence kicks in: welcome video, what to expect on day one, first-class booking.</li>
<li>Soft open with founding members (week before grand open) — they get the gym to themselves for 7-10 days. Powerful loyalty moment.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Channel mix</span>
<h2 class="h2">Where the founding members actually come from</h2>
<p class="body">Typical channel mix for a small boutique opening in a Tier-2 market — based on 150-member presale:</p>
<div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Channel</th><th>Typical share of founding members</th><th>Cost-per-acquired-member</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>Meta paid ads (drive-time targeted)</td><td>30-40%</td><td>$40-$90</td></tr>
<tr><td>Walk-by traffic + construction signage</td><td>20-30%</td><td>$5-$20 (signage cost amortized)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Referral from founding members</td><td>15-25%</td><td>$30-$50 (one month free)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Partner businesses</td><td>10-15%</td><td>$0-$20 (cross-promotion)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Google Search + Local</td><td>5-10%</td><td>$60-$130</td></tr>
<tr><td>Press + organic social</td><td>5-10%</td><td>~$0 marginal</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>The mistake most operators make:</strong> Going 80% Meta and treating presale like a pure paid-acquisition exercise. The walk-by + referral + partner channels are cheaper, higher-converting, and build the local relationships that drive retention later. Paid is a force-multiplier on top, not the foundation.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">AI agents in presale</span>
<h2 class="h2">Where AI agents move the numbers</h2>
<p class="body">Presale is one of the highest-leverage places to use AI agents — not because they replace the founder's relationship-building, but because they handle the high-volume nurture work that's impossible to do by hand and a waste of time to staff up for.</p>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>Lead nurture:</strong> Auto-respond to inbound leads within 60 seconds (vs the 4-24 hour delay most gyms have). 60-second response rate increases lead-to-tour conversion by 30-50%.</li>
<li><strong>Tour scheduling:</strong> Two-way text scheduling without staff involvement. Reduces tour booking friction to a single text exchange.</li>
<li><strong>No-show recovery:</strong> Auto-reschedule outreach 10 minutes after a missed tour. Recovers 25-40% of no-shows.</li>
<li><strong>Founding-member onboarding:</strong> Pre-launch welcome sequence so founding members are warm before the doors open.</li>
<li><strong>FAQ + objection handling:</strong> 24/7 response to "What classes do you offer?" / "What's parking like?" / "Can I freeze my membership?" Frees founder to do high-leverage selling.</li>
</ul>
<p class="body">Purpose-built platform for fitness: <a href="https://fitagentic.ai" style="color:#00C853;">fitagentic.ai</a>. Treetop's coverage of the broader AI agent landscape: <a href="/fitness-operator-prospect-to-member-ai-playbook" style="color:#00C853;">prospect-to-member AI playbook</a>.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Benchmarks</span>
<h2 class="h2">What good looks like</h2>
<div class="table-wrap"><table class="t"><thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th>Struggling (&lt;)</th><th>Typical</th><th>Strong (&gt;)</th></tr></thead><tbody>
<tr><td>Founding members at grand open (vs capacity)</td><td>&lt;20%</td><td>30-50%</td><td>60-70%</td></tr>
<tr><td>Lead-to-tour conversion (paid leads)</td><td>&lt;10%</td><td>15-25%</td><td>30%+</td></tr>
<tr><td>Tour-to-founding-member conversion</td><td>&lt;25%</td><td>30-50%</td><td>60%+</td></tr>
<tr><td>Lead response time</td><td>&gt;4 hours</td><td>5-30 min</td><td>&lt;60 sec (AI agent)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cost per founding member acquired (blended)</td><td>&gt;$150</td><td>$50-$120</td><td>&lt;$40</td></tr>
<tr><td>Referral rate per founding member</td><td>&lt;0.1</td><td>0.2-0.4</td><td>0.5+</td></tr>
</tbody></table></div>
<div class="callout"><p><strong>The single best leading indicator:</strong> Founding members signed by day 30 of the presale. If you've sold 30-50 by day 30, you'll hit 150-200 by grand open. If you've sold under 10 by day 30, something in the offer, pricing, or market fit is broken and waiting another 60 days won't fix it.</p></div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="sec-inner">
<span class="lbl">Common mistakes</span>
<h2 class="h2">Five presale mistakes that hurt month-9 cash position</h2>
<ul class="ul">
<li><strong>1. Starting too late.</strong> Operators who wait until the gym is "ready" before selling lose 60-90 days of cash-flow runway. Start when construction is visibly underway.</li>
<li><strong>2. Pricing the founding offer too high.</strong> 5% discount isn't a founding offer. 30-40% off list is.</li>
<li><strong>3. No cap on the founding cohort.</strong> If anyone who shows up gets the founding rate forever, you've created a structural ARPU problem you'll regret for years.</li>
<li><strong>4. Skipping AI agent nurture.</strong> Slow lead response is the #1 leak in most gym presales. AI agents close that leak for $300-$1K/month.</li>
<li><strong>5. Treating founders as transactions.</strong> Founding members become the loudest evangelists for the brand. Treat them like co-founders, not customers — they'll do more for retention and referral than any other group.</li>
</ul>
</div></section>

